        "content": "<p>I don't understand the question: linear maps are defined using scalar multiplication, in Lean and in \"normal\" math. You take module <code>Mâ‚</code> and <code>Mâ‚‚</code> over a ring <code>R</code> (vector spaces <code>Vâ‚</code> and <code>Vâ‚‚</code> over a field <code>K</code> if you are not familiar with modules. If you are not familiar with fields just take <code>K=â„</code>). Then <code>f : Mâ‚ â†’ Mâ‚‚</code> (<code>f: Vâ‚ â†’ Vâ‚‚</code>) is linear if <code>f(x+y) = f(x) + f(y)</code> and <code>f(Î± â€¢ x) = Î± â€¢ f(x)</code>. Here <code>Î± : R</code> (or <code>Î± : K</code>) is a scalar.</p>",
